s_n
\frac{1}{\sqrt{k}} \ge \frac{2}{\sqrt{k}+\sqrt{k+1}} = 2(\sqrt{k+1}-\sqrt{k}) \ge \frac{1}{\sqrt{k+1}}
\begin{align} & \sum_{k=1}^{n} \frac{1}{\sqrt{k}} \ge 2\sum_{k=1}^{n}(\sqrt{k+1}-\sqrt{k}) = 2(\sqrt{n+1}-1) \ge 2\sqrt{n} - 2\\ \text{and}\quad & \sum_{k=1}^{n} \frac{1}{\sqrt{k}} = 1 + \sum_{k=1}^{n-1} \frac{1}{\sqrt{k+1}} \le 1 + 2\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}(\sqrt{k+1}-\sqrt{k}) = 2\sqrt{n} - 1 \end{align} 
2 - \frac{2}{\sqrt{n}} \le S_n \le 2 - \frac{1}{\sqrt{n}} \quad\implies\quad \lim_{n\to\infty} S_n = 2
\lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{ \sum_{k=1}^n 1/\sqrt{k} }{\sqrt{n}} = \lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{1/\sqrt{n} }{\sqrt{n} - \sqrt{n-1}} = \lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{\sqrt{n}+\sqrt{n-1} }{\sqrt{n}}=2.
